  "base_commit": "80352bf6060acea50ce0b237224f2764e9e5a807",
  "pr_number": 24,
  "issue_number": 23,
  "issue_title": "[Bug] gRPC proxy ignores configured listen host and binds to all interfaces",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\nThe gRPC live-reload proxy advertises and documents `live.reload.proxy.grpc.host`/\n`LIVE_RELOAD_PROXY_GRPC_HOST` as the host to bind the proxy to, defaulting to `localhost`.\n\nIn practice, the gRPC proxy startup path ignores that host and starts the server with only a port:\n\n[GrpcDevServerStart.java] (../jvm-live-reload/core/webserver-grpc/src/main/java/me/seroperson/reload\n/live/webserver/grpc/GrpcDevServerStart.java:68).\n\nThe result is that a user can configure `LIVE_RELOAD_PROXY_GRPC_HOST=127.0.0.1`, see the banner claim `grpc://127.0.0.1:9000`, but the process actually listens on `*:9000`.\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n1. Publish local artifacts:\n\n```sh\nPATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\" \\\nJDK_JAVA_OPTIONS=\"--add-opens=java.base/java.util=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED\" \\\njust\n```\n\n2. Start the sbt gRPC fixture with loopback-only proxy host:\n\n```sh\ncd /jvm-live-reload/sbt/src/test/resources/grpc-scala3\n\nPATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\" \\\nLIVE_RELOAD_PROXY_GRPC_HOST=127.0.0.1 \\\nJDK_JAVA_OPTIONS=\"--add-opens=java.base/java.util=ALL-UNNAMED --add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED\" \\\nsbt -Dproject.version=\"$(../jvm-live-reload/version.txt)\" run\n```\n\n3. Inspect the listening socket:\n```sh\nss -ltnp '( sport = :9000 or sport = :8080 )'\n```\n\n4. Connect to the proxy through the machine\u2019s non-loopback IPv4 address:\n```sh\ntimeout 3 bash -lc 'ip=$(ip -4 addr show scope global | awk '\\''/inet / {sub(\"/.*\", \"\", $2); print $2; exit}'\\''); echo \"testing $ip:9000\"; : < /dev/tcp/$ip/9000; echo CONNECTED'\n```\n5. Make a real gRPC call to the non-loopback address.\n\n## Actual Result\n\nThe banner says the proxy is only on loopback:\n\n```text\nServing at:    grpc://127.0.0.1:9000\n```\n\nBut the kernel socket table shows all-interface bind:\n\n```text\nLISTEN 0 4096 *:9000 *:* users:((\"java\",pid=1713316,fd=189))\n```\n\nTCP connection to the non-loopback address succeeds:\n\n```text\ntesting 37.60.255.86:9000\nCONNECTED\n```\n\nA real gRPC request to the non-loopback address succeeds:\n\n```text\n37.60.255.86 -> Scala3-Hi\n```\nServer logs confirm the external gRPC call triggered the live-reload path:\n\n```text\nProxying method: greeter.Greeter/Greet\nReloading an application\nStarting App\nServer started on port 8080\nFinished reloading\n```\n\n## Expected Result\n\nWhen `LIVE_RELOAD_PROXY_GRPC_HOST=127.0.0.1`, the gRPC proxy should bind only to `127.0.0.1:9000`. Connections to non-loopback interfaces should fail.\n## Evidence\nRelevant docs declare the host setting:\n\n[README.md](https://github.com/seroperson/jvm-live-reload/blob/main/README.md)\n\nRelevant setting exists and defaults to `localhost`:\n\n[DevServerSettings.java]      (https://github.com/seroperson/jvm-live-reload/core/build-link/src/main/java/me/seroperson/reload/live/settings/DevServerSettings.java:99)\n\nThe startup path ignores the host and binds by port only:\n\n[GrpcDevServerStart.java]        (https://github.com/seroperson/jvm-live-reload/blob/main/core/webserver-grpc/src/main/java/me/seroperson/reload/live/webserver/grpc/GrpcDevServerStart.java:68)\n## Root Cause\n\n`GrpcDevServerStart.start()` reads target host/port, but starts the proxy with:\n\n```java\nGrpc.newServerBuilderForPort(settings.getProxyGrpcPort(), proxyCredentials)\n```\n\nThat API binds by port and does not use `settings.getProxyGrpcHost()`. The host is only used later in `getProxyUrl()`, so the banner reflects the configured host while the actual socket does not.\n\n## Security/Business Impact\n\nA developer who expects the gRPC live-reload proxy to be loopback-only can unintentionally expose it to LAN or public network interfaces. Remote clients can reach the dev proxy, trigger app startup/reload/compile behavior, and interact with any gRPC methods exposed by the development application.\n\nThis is especially risky because the proxy is a development tool, likely unauthenticated, and can run against local source/build state.\n\n## Suggested Fix\nBind the gRPC server to an explicit socket address using the configured host:\n\n```java\nvar listenAddress =\n    new InetSocketAddress(settings.getProxyGrpcHost(), settings.getProxyGrpcPort());\n\nproxyServer =\n    Grpc.newServerBuilderForAddress(listenAddress, proxyCredentials)\n        .fallbackHandlerRegistry(new GrpcProxyHandlerRegistry(logger, proxyHandler))\n        .build()\n        .start();\n```\n### JDK Version\n17.0.18\n",
